Title: Add cheap-worker delegation for I/O-heavy tasks (bulk reads, boilerplate)
Created: 2026-05-03
Author: haduong

--- log ---
2026-05-03T15:00Z haduong created

--- body ---
## Context

Claude Code's weekly usage limit is finite. nightbeat and raid sessions burn
through it fast by using the main model for bulk file reads and boilerplate
generation — both tasks that don't need Claude-level reasoning.

Reference: https://medium.com/@kunalbhardwaj598/i-was-burning-through-claude-codes-weekly-limit-in-3-days-here-s-how-i-fixed-it-0344c555abda

Technique: add CLI tools that delegate to a cheap OpenAI-compatible model
(e.g. Kimi K2.5 via Moonshot API, or Claude Haiku via Anthropic API), then
instruct Claude via CLAUDE.md when to delegate. "Claude = thinking. Kimi = I/O."

## Goal

Reduce weekly token burn in nightbeat and interactive sessions by routing
I/O-heavy tasks to a cheap worker, keeping Claude for reasoning only.

## Proposed tools

1. **`scripts/ask-worker <prompt> [file...]`** — Summarize/read files and return
   a compact answer. Use when: reading files >400 lines, or reading 3+ files
   for context gathering. Returns ~400 tokens instead of ~8000.

2. **`scripts/write-worker <prompt>`** — Generate boilerplate (tests, config,
   repetitive scaffolding). Use when: the pattern is predictable and Claude
   would just be filling in a template.

Both tools: call a cheap model via OpenAI-compatible API (configurable via
`WORKER_API_KEY`, `WORKER_BASE_URL`, `WORKER_MODEL` env vars). Falls back
gracefully to "no worker available" so sessions still work without the config.

## CLAUDE.md additions

Add a delegation rule section:

```
## Cheap-worker delegation
When reading files >400 lines, or reading 3+ files for context:
  run: scripts/ask-worker "<question>" <file1> [file2...]
When generating predictable boilerplate (test stubs, config files):
  run: scripts/write-worker "<spec>"
Never delegate: debugging, safety-critical code, design decisions, doc updates.
```

## Implementation options

**Option A — Moonshot/Kimi K2.5** (article's approach): cheap, fast, good at
code reading. Requires `WORKER_BASE_URL=https://api.moonshot.ai/v1`.

**Option B — Claude Haiku via Anthropic API**: same ecosystem, prompt caching
works, but still burns the weekly Claude.ai limit.

**Option C — Local model via Ollama**: free, no rate limit, slower, quality gap.

Recommendation: **A** with env-var abstraction so any option works.

## Acceptance criteria

- `scripts/ask-worker` reads files and returns compact summary; tested with
  a >400-line file
- `scripts/write-worker` generates boilerplate from a spec prompt
- CLAUDE.md instructs when to delegate with clear boundaries
- Both tools degrade gracefully (exit 0 with "worker unavailable" message)
  when WORKER_API_KEY is unset
- Measured: at least one nightbeat raid session uses the worker at least once

## Effort

Medium — ~2 hours. Two short Python scripts + CLAUDE.md edit + env var setup.
